title: For Sale/Trade:  Mle1916 Berthier Carbine
postcontent: I'm looking to sell my 1916 dated Berthier carbine made by Châtellerault, "N" marked, chambered in 8mm Lebel. The stock, barrel, and trigger guard numbers match, and the bolt matches itself. The metal has a patina to it, with wear average with 100-year-old rifles. No pitting that I can see, just a good bit of a mix of dried grease, original finish, and very old, thick paint. The bore is still pretty strong with no pitting. There's a small arsenal repair that has fallen out over the years at the toe of the stock and there's a small crack in top of the handguard. The front barrel band is loose but is easily shimmed. No cleaning rod or rear bottom sling swivel, as these are features that were removed on the "upgrades" the French did to these rifles in the interwar period. This rifle has the overall appearance of what is usually seen with Southeast Asia used/brought back rifles, it is likely it spent some time there. This rifle isn't import marked. Included is 15 rounds of surplus 8mm Lebel and a bag of surplus brass (ammo will ship separately) and 4 original 5-round en bloc clips. I can meet in Athens, Madison, or Huntsville. Feel free to email me or call/text me at 256-43one-425seven with any questions or picture requests. Buyer must have AL drivers license and concealed carry permit or some form of FFL, I will need to get your drivers license number for my C&R bound book. I am asking $260 OBO. I can ship on your dime to 01 or 03 FFL, as well. Thank you, MichaelAlso, to combat spam and scams, I will not accept  cashiers checks or Western Union. title: For Sale:  Rare Limited Scar 17s
postcontent: This is a very rare Limited Initial Production Scar 17s still new in the case. They made less than 500 and even the factory doesnt have an actual number as to how many were made. They made these as a test trial to see how well they would do in the civilian market. They made Limited 16s and 17s. 16s have 7 serial number digits signifying they made over 100,000 of them but the 17s only had 3 serial digit numbers. These first few were first made in the USA at the same plant that they military issues were made. After the first run they moved all production to Belgium. This is gun 186 out of all ever made thus far and continue to produce. They now come in a cardboard box with one mag. The first productions came in a rolling FNH Hardigg Storm case with 2 mags and the Certificate of Authenticity. This one is new and all tags are still on it. Mostly the dealers, ultra high end collectors, and company higher ups scooped most of them up. I have never seen one for sale or sold but have seen one Limited 16s. If you dont know what you are looking at and expect to get it for the same price as a new one dont bother emailing me. I have already sold one. These are so rare I doubt you would ever see another one and certainly not with this low of a serial number. Any other questions email me.

The CZ 75 SP-01 is the first full size handgun (4.6” bbl) from CZ to feature the improved manufacturing technology and ergonomics of the NATO-approved CZ 75 Compact P-01 model. Featuring an integral 1913 accessory rail on the dust cover, rubber grip panels, and CZ’s corrosion resistant black polycoat finish, the SP-01 is the newest model to join the family of pistols based on the CZ 75 (SA/DA) platform. Borrowing from the improved grip geometry of the compact P-01, the SP-01 utilizes an extended beavertail to protect shooter’s strong hand as well as allowing for a deeper and more secure grip. The new grip geometry, checkering in key areas on the front and back straps, and redistribution of mass provided by the accessory rail noticeably decrease the perceived recoil from previous models and allows for more rapid target acquisition and transition.

Thanks to its exceptional accuracy and superior handling characteristics, the CZ 75 SP-01 has also found supporters in the field of sport and target shooting.
